WEBVTT

00:01.668 --> 00:04.002
Buy 50,000 shares
of soy bean futures

00:04.070 --> 00:06.605
and a put option
on the S&P Index

00:06.673 --> 00:07.940
that expires at midnight.

00:08.008 --> 00:10.408
Then dump all the
inflation-protected

00:10.477 --> 00:13.878
treasury bonds
and 15-year CDs.

00:13.948 --> 00:16.548
And then I want you
to move all that cash

00:16.617 --> 00:18.016
into Nikkei Futures.

00:18.085 --> 00:20.285
Liquidate the oil,
put a freeze on gas.
[ Grunts ]

00:20.354 --> 00:23.155
Transfer half my derivatives
into the high-grade portfolio!

00:23.223 --> 00:25.824
Transfer the other half
into the low-grade portfolio!

00:25.892 --> 00:27.426
Then merge those portfolios!

00:27.494 --> 00:31.029
And we're completely clear
of Kappa Kappa Capital, right?

00:31.097 --> 00:32.030
Great.

00:32.098 --> 00:35.634
Man, it is good to be alive.

00:35.702 --> 00:38.637
Oh, and don't forget shares
of Fremulon Insurance.
[ Whirring ]

00:38.705 --> 00:40.172
That stock is on --

00:40.240 --> 00:42.240
[ Screams ] On fire!

00:42.309 --> 00:43.175
[ Screams ]

00:43.243 --> 00:45.043
[ Gunshot ]

00:45.111 --> 00:47.512
♪♪

00:47.514 --> 00:51.316
This is all that remains
of Philip Grammbbowski.

00:51.318 --> 00:55.119
He was a rising star on Wall S--
A.J.: Sorry!

00:55.121 --> 00:56.388
Ugh!

00:56.457 --> 00:59.257
Unbelievable
traffic!

00:59.326 --> 01:03.462
[ Door closes ]

01:03.530 --> 01:05.597
[ Yawns]

01:05.666 --> 01:07.199
[ Cellphone clicking ]

01:07.267 --> 01:10.202
Yaas!

01:10.270 --> 01:11.603
[ Cellphone chimes ]

01:11.672 --> 01:23.482
♪♪

01:23.550 --> 01:35.360
♪♪

01:35.362 --> 01:36.895
Grammbbowski ran
a private wealth fund

01:36.963 --> 01:39.164
worth $4.4 billion
under management.

01:39.166 --> 01:40.765
Whoa.
That's a lot of bread.

01:40.835 --> 01:42.034
Food shame much?

01:42.102 --> 01:43.836
He was a rising star
on Wall Street

01:43.904 --> 01:46.571
until he was ostracized
for his bizarre ideas.

01:46.573 --> 01:49.574
Wait just one
goddamn minute.

01:49.576 --> 01:51.109
We got a first name
on this guy?

01:51.178 --> 01:52.011
Philip.

01:54.181 --> 01:55.180
Makes sense.

01:55.182 --> 01:56.515
He had everything going
for him --

01:56.583 --> 01:58.650
white, male, rich.

01:58.719 --> 02:00.652
An unbeatable combination
until yesterday,

02:00.721 --> 02:02.320
when somebody
tanned him to death.

02:02.389 --> 02:04.523
[ Chuckles ] Serves him right,
the greedy bastard.

02:04.591 --> 02:07.792
Who the hell needs
a billion dollars?
Large countries.

02:07.862 --> 02:09.394
Well-connected
political families.

02:09.396 --> 02:10.595
Billionaires.

02:10.597 --> 02:12.130
Because of the very large
nature of his wealth,

02:12.199 --> 02:13.866
the Special Division Force
is going to figure out

02:13.934 --> 02:16.468
who killed him and why.

02:16.537 --> 02:19.137
Get me some answers,
people.

02:19.206 --> 02:28.681
♪♪

02:28.749 --> 02:38.691
♪♪

02:41.762 --> 02:44.028
Don't bother.
It's password-protected.

02:44.098 --> 02:45.630
Well, it's a good thing
I'm here.

02:45.699 --> 02:46.965
Is it?

02:47.033 --> 02:48.100
What's your problem
with me?

02:48.168 --> 02:50.502
You're overconfident,
hubristic,

02:50.571 --> 02:52.504
aloof, dismissive.

02:52.573 --> 02:54.439
So you can say
something nice.

02:54.441 --> 02:57.910
Now, passwords are an expression
of subconscious thoughts.

02:57.978 --> 03:00.645
You can hide behind it,
but I'll find you.

03:00.714 --> 03:03.916
Talk to me, Philip.
Who are you?

03:03.984 --> 03:06.384
Chicago Cubs pennant.

03:06.453 --> 03:07.652
Ficus plant.

03:07.654 --> 03:10.388
Bowl of M&Ms.

03:10.457 --> 03:12.124
Rothko print.

03:12.192 --> 03:14.058
What's the cat's name?
Mr. Jingles.

03:14.128 --> 03:15.928
Oh, my God!
It's so obvious.

03:15.996 --> 03:17.596
And it's written on
a Post-It note

03:17.664 --> 03:18.863
pasted on his screen.

03:18.865 --> 03:21.266
1-2-3-4-6.
[ Keyboard clacking ]

03:21.335 --> 03:23.535
That's easy to remember.
[ Computer beeps ]

03:23.604 --> 03:25.003
I'm in.

03:25.071 --> 03:27.339
Why don't we try that folder
that says "My Documents"?

03:27.408 --> 03:30.875
It's a Hail Mary,
but let's do it.

03:30.877 --> 03:32.544
This is a list
of Grammbbowski's clients

03:32.613 --> 03:35.013
and what trades he's made
on their behalf.

03:35.081 --> 03:36.949
He moved $1.4 billion

03:37.017 --> 03:38.951
out of something called
Kappa Kappa Capital

03:39.019 --> 03:41.286
the day before he was killed,
but why?

03:41.288 --> 03:43.221
It was one of
his best performers.

03:43.290 --> 03:46.358
And what's this note by
the trade that says "saltine"?

03:46.427 --> 03:48.961
What is that?

03:49.029 --> 03:51.563
Beats me.
Could mean anything.

03:51.632 --> 03:56.568
♪♪

03:56.637 --> 03:59.237
Atkins: Her name
is Norrah Newt.

03:59.306 --> 04:02.374
Sorry, Murphy.
Above your pay grade.

04:02.443 --> 04:05.710
Ms. Newt is --
or should I say is --

04:05.712 --> 04:08.913
a notorious vulture capitalist
and corporate raider.

04:08.983 --> 04:11.116
Her firm,
Kappa Kappa Capital,

04:11.185 --> 04:13.251
is famous
for buying up companies,

04:13.320 --> 04:15.453
selling them for their parts,
then buying those parts

04:15.522 --> 04:18.190
and putting them back together
to form the original company.

04:18.258 --> 04:20.125
Sounds like a real
stand-up gal.

04:20.194 --> 04:22.060
Not since she left comedy
15 years ago

04:22.129 --> 04:23.528
and started day-trading.

04:23.597 --> 04:26.465
Now her company is worth
57 billion and one dollars.

04:26.533 --> 04:28.266
That's some
serious cheese.

04:28.335 --> 04:31.069
It's part of my cleanse.
We found out Grammbbowski

04:31.137 --> 04:33.538
recently pulled
nearly $1.5 billion

04:33.607 --> 04:35.940
of his clients' money
out of Kappa Kappa Capital.

04:36.010 --> 04:39.277
So Newt gets her revenge by
frying Grammbbowski to a crisp.

04:39.346 --> 04:41.880
It's possible,
but we don't have any proof.

04:41.948 --> 04:43.415
That's why we're going
undercover

04:43.484 --> 04:45.750
in the complex, aggressive world
of high finance.

04:45.752 --> 04:46.951
A.J.: With all due
respect, sir,

04:46.953 --> 04:48.353
I'm gonna have to sit
this one out.

04:48.422 --> 04:50.155
These Wall Street scumbags
have created an economy

04:50.224 --> 04:51.490
that only works
for the rich.

04:51.558 --> 04:53.892
We can sing their praises
all day long,

04:53.960 --> 04:55.627
but we still have
a job to do.

04:55.696 --> 04:59.297
Our next stop is the financial
capital of the world --

04:59.366 --> 05:00.965
Des Moines, Iowa.

05:00.967 --> 05:02.234
<i> Now, the world of finance has</i>

05:02.302 --> 05:04.503
<i> changed a lot</i>
<i> in the last 30 years.</i>

05:04.571 --> 05:08.841
<i> It's absolutely nothing like</i>
<i> '80s movies about Wall Street.</i>

05:08.909 --> 05:10.509
[ Elevator bell dings ]

05:10.577 --> 05:16.849
♪♪

05:16.917 --> 05:18.650
Hey, Tribeca.
How's it going?

05:18.719 --> 05:20.785
Can't wait for tomorrow 'cause
I get better looking every day.

05:20.787 --> 05:22.187
Love the hair,
by the way.

05:22.256 --> 05:24.256
Flattery will get you
everywhere.
Counting on it.

05:24.324 --> 05:26.191
Hey, Scholls, how was
your date last night?

05:26.193 --> 05:27.860
Are you kidding?
I took her to Mostaccioli's.

05:27.928 --> 05:29.862
It was a sure thing.
How'd you get a rez there?

05:29.930 --> 05:32.865
Banged the manager.
[ Chuckles ]

05:32.933 --> 05:35.200
♪♪

05:35.269 --> 05:38.070
Hey, Hoffman, loving the tie.
Bill Blass?

05:38.138 --> 05:39.471
What's happening, Charo?

05:39.540 --> 05:41.940
I have no reference point
for this era.

05:42.008 --> 05:43.275
♪♪

05:43.343 --> 05:45.610
Morning, son.
What looks good?

05:45.679 --> 05:47.079
Oh, I don't know --
People being able

05:47.147 --> 05:48.480
to raise themselves
out of poverty,

05:48.549 --> 05:50.082
having a chance
at a good education,

05:50.150 --> 05:51.283
a middle class.

05:51.351 --> 05:53.151
You are treading
on thin ice, mister.

05:53.220 --> 05:54.486
Now lose the attitude

05:54.555 --> 05:56.821
and cheat some people
out of their money.

05:56.891 --> 06:00.225
[ Telephone rings in distance ]

06:00.294 --> 06:02.227
Hello, this is Angela Geils
from Kappa Kappa Capital.

06:02.296 --> 06:04.296
Did you know that there are some
very interesting opportunities

06:04.365 --> 06:07.165
available in the stock market
that you might not be aware of?

06:07.234 --> 06:09.301
Man:<i> Oh, yeah?</i>
<i> What are they?</i>

06:09.370 --> 06:12.504
Uh, for example, you could
buy something called

06:12.573 --> 06:16.241
Scabuble Shaving Systems.
<i> That sounds great.</i>

06:16.243 --> 06:17.642
<i> Put me down for</i>
<i> a million dollars' worth.</i>

06:17.711 --> 06:20.512
Uh, sir, I don't recommend --
<i> Make it two million.</i>

06:20.581 --> 06:23.848
<i> I got to go.</i>

06:23.918 --> 06:27.185
Here's your commission,
Mr. Geils.

06:27.254 --> 06:28.721
Oh, my God, I'm rich!

06:28.789 --> 06:33.057
Ms. Newt wants
to see you.

06:33.059 --> 06:36.428
♪♪

06:40.334 --> 06:42.867
[ Indistinct chatter ]

06:42.937 --> 06:48.873
♪♪

06:48.943 --> 06:50.875
Norrah Newt.
Have a seat, A.J.

06:50.877 --> 06:52.811
[ Door closes ]

06:52.879 --> 06:55.213
♪♪

06:55.282 --> 06:56.748
It's a papasan chair.

06:56.817 --> 06:59.752
Invented by the Japanese
as a place to sit awkwardly.

06:59.820 --> 07:03.421
♪♪

07:03.490 --> 07:04.022
Oh!

07:04.091 --> 07:05.624
Shit.

07:17.104 --> 07:20.305
I like it.

07:20.307 --> 07:21.440
It's different.

07:21.508 --> 07:23.041
Did you know there's
no Japanese word

07:23.109 --> 07:23.976
for "business"?

07:24.044 --> 07:25.910
Isn't it "bijinesu"?

07:25.980 --> 07:28.447
Maybe there is.

07:28.515 --> 07:30.715
Heard you made your first
big commission today.

07:30.717 --> 07:34.052
Yes, ma'am. Uh...
Scabuble Shaving Systems.

07:34.120 --> 07:35.120
It's garbage.

07:35.189 --> 07:37.522
It's up 21% on the year.
Exactly.

07:37.591 --> 07:39.257
And in tomorrow's news,
there will be a story about

07:39.326 --> 07:41.126
a man who sliced his neck open
with a Scabuble razor,

07:41.195 --> 07:42.727
and that story will be
planted by me,

07:42.729 --> 07:45.730
but not before I've unloaded
every last one of my shares.

07:45.800 --> 07:46.999
That's totally immoral.

07:47.067 --> 07:48.600
This is a $75,000 watch.

07:48.669 --> 07:50.569
Let me see what you got
on your wrist.

07:52.739 --> 07:55.073
Is that moral, that you should
have cheap things

07:55.141 --> 07:56.941
while I enjoy
the best of everything?

07:56.943 --> 07:58.210
I-I'm happy with
what I have.

07:58.278 --> 08:00.479
Only because you've
never had more.

08:00.547 --> 08:03.482
Come here.
Let me show you something.

08:08.955 --> 08:11.023
Cute kid, huh?

08:11.091 --> 08:13.092
I'm thinking of
buying her.

08:15.229 --> 08:17.429
This is me the day
my parents abandoned me.

08:17.498 --> 08:19.297
I bounced around foster homes
till age 15,

08:19.366 --> 08:21.033
when I started
my own business

08:21.101 --> 08:22.567
buying and selling
foster homes.

08:22.636 --> 08:26.771
By age 20,
I made my first trillion.

08:26.773 --> 08:28.707
Did your parents ever
abandon you, A.J.?

08:28.775 --> 08:30.175
Only once.

08:30.244 --> 08:31.376
Probably made you
pretty vulnerable

08:31.445 --> 08:32.911
to sympathetic
authority figures.

08:32.979 --> 08:35.447
That's not Mom.
I mean, true.

08:35.516 --> 08:37.649
We're gonna go places,
buddy.

08:37.718 --> 08:42.120
♪♪

08:42.189 --> 08:43.856
Here's a million bucks.

08:43.924 --> 08:45.724
A kid's got to have some
walkin' around money.

08:45.792 --> 08:47.192
Wow! Thanks.

08:47.261 --> 08:48.527
All right.
Get out of here.

08:48.595 --> 08:49.794
I got to be staring
out the window

08:49.864 --> 08:50.995
for my next meeting.

08:50.997 --> 08:58.537
♪♪

08:58.605 --> 08:59.872
[ Sighs ]

08:59.940 --> 09:01.674
[ Door opens ]
All right, then.

09:01.742 --> 09:03.808
We've successfully
infiltrated the company.

09:03.878 --> 09:05.878
Now it's time to start
poking a few bears,

09:05.946 --> 09:08.813
see if we can get them to crap
out some honey.

09:08.883 --> 09:11.483
How was your one-on-one
with Newt, A.J.?

09:11.552 --> 09:13.485
It was okay,
I guess.
Really?

09:13.554 --> 09:15.487
I thought you were totally
disgusted by her.

09:15.556 --> 09:18.090
The greed, the excess,
the possible murder.

09:18.158 --> 09:20.092
Hey, we have
nothing on her.

09:20.160 --> 09:22.094
Everything you just said
is pure speculation,

09:22.162 --> 09:23.562
except for the greed
and the excess.

09:23.630 --> 09:26.298
Sorry, I didn't realize
you were best friends now.

09:26.366 --> 09:28.300
Well, we are.
A-A-Another thing.

09:28.369 --> 09:30.302
Why are we all so poor?

09:30.370 --> 09:31.904
I mean, all we need to do
is buy stocks,

09:31.972 --> 09:34.172
sabotage the company --
We'd be on Easy Street.

09:34.241 --> 09:36.575
Wow, that's a lot
to take in.

09:36.643 --> 09:38.643
[ Mumbling ]

09:38.645 --> 09:40.445
Whatever.
I need to go back to work.

09:40.447 --> 09:42.614
Money don't sleep.

09:45.852 --> 09:47.719
[ Door closes ]
I don't know about you,

09:47.788 --> 09:51.055
but I am starting to really
like him.
I'm worried.

09:51.057 --> 09:54.126
You remember back in the day,
Mahoney and the aquarium op?

09:54.194 --> 09:55.727
Mahoney was diagnosed
with schizophrenia

09:55.796 --> 09:58.130
long before he decided to live
as a manta ray.

09:58.198 --> 10:00.732
[ Sighs ]

10:00.801 --> 10:02.134
[ Door opens ]

10:02.202 --> 10:05.604
Uh, Dr. Stolls?
Can I talk to you?

10:05.672 --> 10:06.805
It's Scholls.

10:06.873 --> 10:11.209
♪♪

10:11.278 --> 10:12.411
When I was a sophomore,

10:12.479 --> 10:13.878
I wrote my Behavioral
Economics paper

10:13.948 --> 10:16.081
on the relationship
between saltine crackers

10:16.150 --> 10:17.349
and the United States
economy.

10:17.417 --> 10:18.683
I thought it was odd
when you smashed

10:18.752 --> 10:20.953
Grammbbowski's computer,
but now it's paying off.

10:21.021 --> 10:22.421
Go on.
Well, the paper

10:22.489 --> 10:23.822
got some attention
on Wall Street

10:23.890 --> 10:25.690
before it was
universally dismissed,

10:25.692 --> 10:28.160
except by one person --
Philip Grammbbowski.

10:28.228 --> 10:31.296
Why are you telling me this?
I thought you hated me.

10:31.298 --> 10:34.499
Well, I guess I was afraid of
being laughed at by everyone.

10:34.568 --> 10:36.301
But since you're not
someone I look up to,

10:36.303 --> 10:39.103
I figured it was
a pretty safe bet.

10:39.105 --> 10:40.238
Thank you.

10:40.307 --> 10:42.040
That means a lot.

10:42.108 --> 10:44.777
Let's go get
that paper.

10:44.845 --> 10:46.911
[ Gong sounding ]

10:46.981 --> 10:50.582
[ Sniffing ]

10:50.651 --> 10:52.651
Whoo!
Listen up, everybody!

10:52.719 --> 10:54.853
I am pleased to announce
Kappa Kappa Capital's

10:54.921 --> 10:57.389
next billion dollar
sales contest winner.

10:57.458 --> 10:59.057
You know him, you love him,

10:59.125 --> 11:00.392
you don't really know him.

11:00.461 --> 11:02.260
A.J. Pseudonym!

11:02.329 --> 11:05.263
[ Cheers and applause ]

11:05.332 --> 11:14.739
♪♪

11:14.741 --> 11:23.816
♪♪

11:23.884 --> 11:25.617
-Todd!
-Coming!

11:25.686 --> 11:30.422
♪♪

11:30.491 --> 11:33.625
[ All cheering ]

11:33.694 --> 11:35.894
♪♪

11:35.962 --> 11:37.229
Aaaah!

11:37.297 --> 11:40.432
Whooo!
[ Laughs ]

11:40.501 --> 11:52.777
♪♪

11:52.847 --> 11:54.246
[ Groans ]

11:54.314 --> 11:56.048
[ Sighs ]

11:56.116 --> 11:59.317
♪♪

11:59.386 --> 12:02.320
♪♪

12:02.389 --> 12:03.922
You done good, kid.

12:03.990 --> 12:05.590
You made a lot of money
for the company.

12:05.592 --> 12:07.592
That's only gonna
increase our profits.

12:07.594 --> 12:09.261
I'm just doing
what you told me.

12:09.329 --> 12:11.830
Kickin' ass
and takin' names.

12:16.136 --> 12:16.935
Charles.

12:17.003 --> 12:19.738
♪♪

12:19.806 --> 12:22.607
But it's all been
small potatoes so far.

12:22.676 --> 12:25.610
Can we get some
steaks over here?

12:25.679 --> 12:27.546
How much money did you
make this week?

12:27.614 --> 12:30.683
I don't know.
50, 52 billion.

12:30.751 --> 12:32.016
Peanuts.

12:32.086 --> 12:35.019
Linus is trying to give up
his blanket.

12:35.089 --> 12:37.222
It's time we took down
the whole enchilada.

12:37.291 --> 12:39.291
Server: Hot plate.
[ Sizzling ]

12:39.359 --> 12:41.960
I got to say,
$52 billion

12:42.028 --> 12:43.962
kind of covers my nut.

12:44.030 --> 12:49.702
♪♪

12:49.770 --> 12:53.706
But why settle for $52 billion
when you could have $53 billion?

12:53.774 --> 12:55.507
Immoral is one thing,
but we're not talking

12:55.576 --> 12:57.175
about anything
illegal here, are we?

12:57.244 --> 12:59.444
What's the matter?
You scared?

12:59.446 --> 13:00.979
No, I'm not scared.

13:01.047 --> 13:03.047
It's not like your mom's gonna
be disappointed in you.

13:03.049 --> 13:04.649
Wh-What are you
talking about?

13:04.651 --> 13:06.318
Because you said you were
an orphan like me.

13:06.387 --> 13:08.186
Oh, yeah, yes.

13:08.255 --> 13:10.855
T-Totally.
Absolutely no parents.

13:10.857 --> 13:13.125
Right.
So let's do this.

13:13.193 --> 13:14.927
Let's raid the biggest
corporation there is --

13:14.995 --> 13:18.330
the United States
of America.

13:18.398 --> 13:19.664
Sign me up.

13:19.733 --> 13:22.000
Great.
You're in.

13:22.068 --> 13:24.136
You're just gonna need
a swim suit, a towel,

13:24.204 --> 13:25.870
and a bag lunch.

13:25.872 --> 13:27.539
♪♪

13:31.278 --> 13:32.844
All right.

13:32.913 --> 13:34.446
Let's hear this
cockamamie theory.
I'm nervous.

13:34.514 --> 13:36.648
Just picture them
in their underwear.

13:41.655 --> 13:44.856
Webster's defines economics
as the, uh...

13:44.925 --> 13:46.858
Two years ago,
the saltine cracker market

13:46.927 --> 13:48.860
took a nose dive,
and I wanted to know why,

13:48.929 --> 13:50.662
from a behavioral economic
perspective.

13:50.731 --> 13:52.397
So I dug a little deeper.

13:52.466 --> 13:53.999
Why aren't people
buying saltines?

13:54.067 --> 13:56.134
-Soup.
-Exactly.

13:56.136 --> 13:57.603
People aren't eating soup
anymore.

13:57.671 --> 14:00.806
That's ridiculous!
I had soup as recently as --

14:00.874 --> 14:03.809
Oh, my God.
She is right.

14:03.877 --> 14:05.543
Wait.

14:05.545 --> 14:06.878
I have no idea
what we're talking about.

14:06.947 --> 14:09.815
Why has the soup market
suddenly gone lukewarm?

14:09.883 --> 14:11.683
Why? Tell us.
No, I'm asking you.

14:11.752 --> 14:14.219
That's as far as I got
with my paper.

14:14.288 --> 14:17.555
I, uh...
only got a "C."

14:17.557 --> 14:18.957
Scholls: People
aren't eating soup

14:18.959 --> 14:20.558
because the Earth is
getting warmer.

14:20.628 --> 14:22.027
And you know what
that means.

14:22.096 --> 14:24.095
Of course! Wait.

14:24.164 --> 14:26.097
I still have no idea
how this relates to anything.

14:26.166 --> 14:28.166
Think about this --
It's a hot day.

14:28.235 --> 14:30.235
You want to take a casual walk
around the block.

14:30.304 --> 14:31.637
But what do wear?

14:31.705 --> 14:33.171
You'll roast in a pair
of long pants,

14:33.173 --> 14:34.572
so you reach in your closet
and pull out --

14:34.574 --> 14:35.641
Jean shorts.

14:35.709 --> 14:37.242
Jean shorts are
the Achilles heel

14:37.311 --> 14:40.646
of the entire U.S. economy,
and Philip Grammbbowski knew it.

14:40.714 --> 14:42.714
He knew that if anything
were to disrupt that market,

14:42.783 --> 14:45.117
the whole financial system
comes crashing down.

14:45.185 --> 14:47.585
And guess who's been buying up
every denim factory

14:47.587 --> 14:49.121
from North Korea
to South Korea?

14:49.189 --> 14:50.456
I am so sorry, guys.

14:50.524 --> 14:52.057
I'm not even close
to being on this train.

14:52.125 --> 14:53.725
Could you demonstrate
with a Jenga tower

14:53.794 --> 14:56.061
or maybe some oranges?

14:56.130 --> 14:57.595
Norrah Newt is
going to buy up

14:57.597 --> 14:59.197
all of the denim
and collapse the market.

14:59.266 --> 15:00.932
Grammbbowski found out
what she was doing,

15:01.001 --> 15:03.935
pulled out all of his money,
and ended up as turkey jerky.

15:04.004 --> 15:06.138
Why does Newt want to sink
the U.S. economy?

15:06.206 --> 15:08.073
I can't imagine
she's acting alone,

15:08.142 --> 15:10.075
but my son is the only one
who can answer that question,

15:10.144 --> 15:12.077
but he has gone
full Donnie Brasco.

15:12.146 --> 15:13.611
So take him out.

15:13.613 --> 15:14.412
He's my son.

15:14.482 --> 15:15.547
Oh, shit, right.

15:15.615 --> 15:16.948
But maybe taking him out

15:17.017 --> 15:19.685
is exactly what
this situation requires.

15:19.753 --> 15:22.020
I swear to God, I didn't
make the connection!
[ Door opens ]

15:22.022 --> 15:23.355
Don't kill him!
[ Door closes ]

15:23.423 --> 15:25.023
Great.

15:25.025 --> 15:26.624
Thank you.

15:26.694 --> 15:28.760
Gap, Levi's, Jordache,

15:28.829 --> 15:31.897
and Osh Kosh B'Gosh
all ours.

15:31.965 --> 15:35.167
We now own 98% of all
jean short production.

15:35.235 --> 15:36.301
I'm proud of you, A.J.

15:36.370 --> 15:38.303
[ Sighs ]
Freeze! S.E.C.!

15:38.372 --> 15:40.372
Wh--
Let's go, dirtbag.

15:40.440 --> 15:42.040
Stay strong and keep
your mouth shut.

15:42.042 --> 15:44.910
I said move it!
Okay, take it easy, man!

15:44.978 --> 15:46.244
♪♪

15:46.313 --> 15:47.179
Easy.

15:47.247 --> 15:48.380
Ow!

15:48.448 --> 15:49.581
[ Telephones ringing ]

15:49.649 --> 15:51.517
I don't know who
you are or --

15:51.585 --> 15:52.984
Mom?! What the hell
are you doing?

15:53.053 --> 15:54.786
I want to show you
something.

15:54.855 --> 15:56.522
Mom, what the hell
are you doing?

15:56.590 --> 15:59.057
I want to show you something.
[ Elevator bell dings ]

15:59.126 --> 16:00.658
Mom, what the hell
are you doing?

16:00.660 --> 16:01.927
I want to show you
something.

16:01.995 --> 16:03.395
Ow!

16:03.463 --> 16:04.863
[ Indistinct talking ]

16:04.865 --> 16:06.331
You know who that is?

16:06.400 --> 16:08.666
...sales are down 20%.

16:08.736 --> 16:10.402
No idea.

16:10.470 --> 16:11.870
That's Bobson Dugnutt.

16:11.939 --> 16:15.541
He's the former C.E.O.
of Scabuble Shaving Systems.

16:15.609 --> 16:17.209
What's he doing<i> here?</i>

16:17.277 --> 16:19.277
Well, since you
and Newt torpedoed

16:19.346 --> 16:21.012
his Fortune 500 company,

16:21.081 --> 16:22.548
he had to take a job
as a C.E.O.

16:22.616 --> 16:25.083
at a slightly smaller
company.

16:25.085 --> 16:27.753
He used to manage
5,500 employees.

16:27.821 --> 16:31.623
Now he manages 3,500.

16:31.691 --> 16:32.958
I didn't know.

16:33.026 --> 16:36.494
No, you didn't know,
because you don't stop to think

16:36.496 --> 16:38.430
about the human beings
behind the numbers.

16:38.498 --> 16:40.899
Get out of the way!

16:40.901 --> 16:44.502
He had to trade
in his G5 for a G4.

16:44.572 --> 16:47.373
And look at his suit.
I --

16:47.441 --> 16:49.707
It looks like --
Looks like
it's right off the rack?

16:49.709 --> 16:51.709
I'm gonna be sick.

16:51.711 --> 16:53.845
That's the
Norrah Newt Effect.

16:53.914 --> 16:57.849
You still want
to be part of it?

16:57.918 --> 17:00.318
[ Strained ]
I don't know.

17:00.320 --> 17:02.788
Why is Newt trying to collapse
the jean short market?

17:02.856 --> 17:04.456
[ Voice breaking ]
I'm in too deep, Mom. I can't.

17:04.524 --> 17:06.124
Damn it, A.J.!

17:06.193 --> 17:08.060
I know things have been
hard for you, okay?

17:08.128 --> 17:10.128
I know I wasn't there
for you.

17:10.130 --> 17:11.797
But none of that
matters now.

17:11.865 --> 17:15.067
You have to decide
who you want to be.

17:15.135 --> 17:17.135
I'm sorry, Mom.

17:17.204 --> 17:20.071
I guess I just love money
too much now.

17:20.140 --> 17:22.474
♪♪

17:22.542 --> 17:24.209
Take him away.

17:24.278 --> 17:26.278
What?
[ Handcuffs click ]

17:26.346 --> 17:28.213
What? I don't --
[ Handcuffs click ]

17:28.282 --> 17:30.348
[ Groans ] Mom...

17:30.417 --> 17:32.550
Mom!

17:32.620 --> 17:35.954
♪♪

17:40.194 --> 17:43.595
♪♪

17:43.664 --> 17:46.131
I'm proud of you, buddy.
You made the right decision.

17:46.200 --> 17:48.266
[ Sighing ] If I'm going
all the way with this,

17:48.335 --> 17:50.535
I want to know
I'm gonna be mega rich,

17:50.537 --> 17:53.605
like don't bother bringing the
Bed Bath & Beyond coupon rich.

17:53.674 --> 17:54.807
I think you'll find
the U.S. Treasury

17:54.875 --> 17:56.608
has everything
you're looking for.

17:56.677 --> 17:58.276
Once the French government
gives us the go-ahead,

17:58.345 --> 18:01.079
we'll make our move and watch
the economy go into free fall.

18:01.148 --> 18:03.015
So the French are the ones
staking you?

18:03.083 --> 18:04.148
That's right.

18:04.150 --> 18:05.884
But by the time this
whole thing burns down,

18:05.952 --> 18:08.553
we'll be on an island
in the middle of Lake Michigan.

18:08.555 --> 18:10.955
I'm in.

18:11.025 --> 18:13.558
I just need to use
the bathroom first.

18:13.560 --> 18:15.627
You're gonna use
a park bathroom?

18:15.696 --> 18:18.197
It's an emergency.

18:19.966 --> 18:22.234
Ooh.

18:22.302 --> 18:24.703
I think I got it.

18:24.771 --> 18:26.571
[ Grunts ]

18:26.573 --> 18:28.907
[ Record scratching ]
Tape's no good.
We need it again.

18:28.975 --> 18:30.308
What?
Are you kidding me?

18:30.377 --> 18:31.844
She's totally gonna
suspect something.

18:31.912 --> 18:34.312
Just get her to run down
the basics, then get out.

18:34.381 --> 18:35.780
[ Sighs ]

18:35.782 --> 18:37.249
Once the French government
gives us the go-ahead,

18:37.317 --> 18:40.052
we'll make our move and watch
the economy go into free fall.

18:40.120 --> 18:41.986
So the French are the ones
staking you?

18:41.988 --> 18:43.788
That's right,
but by the time

18:43.858 --> 18:45.924
this whole thing burns down,
we'll be on an island

18:45.992 --> 18:48.060
<i> in the middle of</i>
<i> Lake Michigan.</i>

18:48.128 --> 18:49.728
Too much interference.
We didn't get it.

18:49.796 --> 18:50.995
Come on, man!

18:50.997 --> 18:53.398
One more time,
and we are out of here.

18:53.467 --> 18:55.267
[ Sighs ]

18:55.335 --> 18:57.069
But by the time this
whole thing burns down,

18:57.137 --> 19:01.339
we'll be on an island
in the middle of Lake Michigan.

19:01.408 --> 19:02.941
Wait a second.

19:03.009 --> 19:05.610
♪♪

19:05.612 --> 19:08.680
Are you wearing a wire?

19:08.749 --> 19:11.149
You son of a bitch!

19:11.218 --> 19:13.818
You could've had everything.
You could've been me.

19:13.888 --> 19:15.620
I guess I did fantasize
about being you

19:15.689 --> 19:16.889
for the last day
and a quarter.

19:16.957 --> 19:18.356
But in the end,

19:18.425 --> 19:21.359
I need to be someone
who makes his mom proud.

19:21.428 --> 19:23.361
You have a parent?!

19:23.430 --> 19:26.365
♪♪

19:26.433 --> 19:28.233
A.J.:<i> But in the end,</i>

19:28.302 --> 19:31.169
<i> I need to be someone</i>
<i> who makes his mom proud.</i>

19:31.238 --> 19:33.838
[ Click ]

19:33.840 --> 19:36.441
Do I have to give
the money back?

19:36.510 --> 19:37.642
Afraid so, kid.

19:37.711 --> 19:40.712
[ Scoffs ]

19:40.781 --> 19:42.647
Scholls, what's happening
on Wall Street?

19:42.649 --> 19:45.117
The markets have stabilized,
and the Treasury Department

19:45.185 --> 19:47.385
is raiding Kappa Kappa Capital
as we speak.

19:47.454 --> 19:49.053
Charo: And from
a behavioral perspective,

19:49.123 --> 19:51.189
people are confident
in the economy again.

19:51.258 --> 19:53.057
Atkins:
Good work, people.

19:53.127 --> 19:54.727
Good work.

19:54.795 --> 19:56.661
Now let's head back
to Los Angeles.

19:56.730 --> 19:59.131
♪♪

19:59.199 --> 20:02.001
I'm desperate to do
a load of laundry.

20:03.738 --> 20:16.081
♪♪

20:16.150 --> 20:28.193
♪♪
